= Dharma talk: You're Not Aware---Aware is You

This one’s important.  Because it has to do with why we start wanting to smoke and drink and do all this stuff.  

So one important point that I made earlier is:  when you recognize awareness—and at first you may struggle with that recognition—remember, many masters, we always cite Niguma’s “Four Faults”, where she says it’s so simple that you don’t accept it.  It’s very very powerful, and we don’t embrace that.  And I think, through the sharings today, we saw some of the resistors that go up.  And that’s fine; it’s just not our time to come into that yet.  

But if you’ve been introduced, if you’ve connected with this, then there’s an opportunity to see pure consciousness, that holds all states of consciousness, just like the river would hold all the waves, or the flow, or the ocean would hold all the waves, or the whirlpool in the lake, or something like that.  No experience ever departs from the pure basis.  That’s why this practice can be very very powerful.  You get introduced, right?  Pointing out, mind-to-mind, is very effective.  If we just sit here right now, eye-to-eye, relaxing into presence… (Dawai pauses)  You see, and any thought, any sound, any sight, is all within this pure aspect of mind.  

I’ll keep talking—you try to remove the words from your mind as I keep talking, okay?  See if you can do it.  See if you can delete the words out of your awareness.  You wish you could sometimes, but you can’t.

Just like that, all thoughts, any thought that you could ever have, is permeated by this pristine, wakeful, purely present mind.  It has to be there, to hold everything else.  Waves have to exist on the water.  Thoughts have to exist on the basis of the mind.  It’s cognition; waves of cognition within a field of cognition.  

And that cognition isn’t limited to subjectivity, because subjectivity is within that cognition.  You can feel a sense of “me” sitting here.  So you’re not aware—aware is you.  (Dawai pauses) 

Any feeling of me being aware of something is within this great room, this great auditorium of awareness.  

So remember that, everybody, especially in the ten minute short meditations, if you could do those in the forest, by the river, on a hill, wherever.  If you can do ten minutes of just letting be, like water into water, you let this whole body, and emotion, thoughts, you just let it relax into the presence… and then you can now operate from the basis.  You can speak, and act, and play games, and go crazy, whatever.  But now you’re out of the whirlpool, into the lake.  You're out of the movie and into the screen.  

So we follow the lineage of practitioners, meditation yogi lineages, that they get used to this through short sessions, repeated many times.  And so maybe I was able to soak my experience today in the ten minutes, and some things sort of came off of me, some things eased up:  my nervous system, my muscles, my experience, started to go back to normal.  But maybe not all of it.  Maybe there’s still some lumps of dissatisfaction and discontent.  

So then I go and I take a walk, but now I’m that much more used to being in awareness, because of the short session.  Or, our whole session, actually here, is getting us used to just  this pure present aspect of our mind:  the heart-mind.  It takes care of you.  The more you lean into it, the more you prove to yourself that this mind is even there, then it will take care of you.  

And when we’re ready, the deepest stuff unlocks out of our consciousness, you know?  Traumas that we’ve had, and grudges that we hold, and discontentment—these things unlock and all the sudden you find yourself… You might be sitting there with a cigarette in your hand, and no reason to smoke it.”Wait a minute, I’m not even stressing!”  (Dawai pantomimes holding a cigarette, looking down at it, and tossing it away.)… Yeah.

(Dawai responds to someone wanting to speak) Yes, please, chime on in there.

SANGHA 1:  I’m wondering if you could tell me if there’s like an intelligence to the awareness, like is it also really, like… this awareness, that I’m familiarizing myself with in this practice, is it also intelligence?  ‘Cause that’s another thing that I’m thinking.  Like, it appears, like it’s very… it’s intelligent, but it doesn’t have a thought to it.  It’s weird; it’s different than the kind of intelligence I learned in school, it seems like. 

DAWAI:  Do you remember the pointing out we did?  

SANGHA 1:  Yeah, I do.  

DAWAI:  That really landed for you, because that’s exactly it.  In fact, I define it as “living intelligence.”  And it just so happens that it has a lot in common with, like, Unified Fields, like empty space being alive. 

Now, it’s not sitting there doing math problems, right? Not that kind of intelligence, like [Sangha 1]’s saying.  It’s a different kind of—it’s the basis for all intelligence.  That’s what we have to remember, when we fight with this analytically, or anything:  that waves have to happen on the water.  Thoughts, ideas, beliefs have to happen on the water of aware… you know, of cognition.  Those are intelligences happening in the field of intelligence.  And that field is invisible, so we completely neglect it. 

And we get caught up in referentiality, just like when you go to sleep and you have a dream, you think you’re in that subject.  The mind-play is hinting to you there, “Look, I’m tricking you, I’m convincing, I’m creating a world, and then creating a subjectivity within that world, and you think you’re in that subjectivity, when you’re really the whole dang world!”  Yeah.

And then you start to see the natural weather, and here’s the important point of this whole talk, okay everybody?  I want you to understand this, as sort of mind masters, I mean, there’s a huge live gathering here right now, and you all are true masters.  They have many words for this intelligence that [Sangha 1]’s…you know, [Sangha 1]’s calling it “intelligence,” which is a little bit… expands it, makes it more high-tech than maybe “awareness.”  The word “awareness” is a little bit reductive, but it’s more accessible than “intelligence.”  So I believe having, you know, a vast nomenclature for different contexts is more appropriate.  So, they have beautiful terms for this, like bodhicitta, the Tibetan word rigpa, or the Sanskrit word vidya, or mahasandhi.  Beautiful, beautiful words for this, even more than that, right?  

So,”awareness” is just one word.  It opens up the doors of the infinite, ineffable majesty of the mind.  We have to get you through the door somehow.  We have to introduce you somehow.  And you can’t be introduced purely analytically, purely intellectually, conceptually.  ‘Cause then you’re still gonna be stuck in a smaller dimension.  We gotta get you out of the concepts, into the whole mind.  Even if we use concepts to get there, that’s fine, but I think definitely in this type of approach here that you’ll see in our gatherings, it has the outer, inner, and secret way of landing on people.  You could disagree with every single word I’m saying, and the view is still landing on you.  It’s great.  See?  You’re always right, when you’re a lama!

So let me get back to this very important point, because I want to set up a protection, just like I think Nagarjuna, and Shantideva,  many who advised to guard the mind, protect the mind—well, in dzogchen we have a similar aspect that we’re dealing with.  But, you have to zoom out .  You can’t take credit for every little happening, every little bad feeling that you have.  You can’t keep taking credit for that, and owning it.  It might just be the way the moon is today.  The way the earth is rotating.  I mean, they have so many energies out there now, technological energies and earthly energies…

We take responsibility for so much.  That would be like the flower saying “Oh god, I got raindrops on me, I’m just a wet flower, I’m always such a wet flower—nobody likes me ‘cause I’m wet!”  You know, the flower doesn’t do that.  Or the wind blows, and the flower’s like “Oh my goodness, my leaves are just going crazy —what’s wrong with me?”

So, it comes back to echoes, everybody.  You could get in a discussion with somebody, and not even know that that’s echoing in your consciousness.  Now awareness holders, awareness practitioners who are really coming to that pristine, subtle level, they will know every little trace, anything that enters—it’s like a room.  You have this blank room, and any little object that comes into your room (Dawai leans forward, grabs an object, and shows it to the sangha)—you know it.
  
But here we’re talking about echoes.  Like you just had a conversation with somebody (Dawai rings the meditation cymbals in his hand). You have to let that echo out.  And it may take a day or two. (Dawai rings the cymbals again)  It may take longer, for things, certain things that… You don’t even know.  You could have watched a video; you could have had an interaction with your family.  And you don’t know that that’s lingering in your consciousness for two days.  

Sometimes we get addicted to disturbing things, to drama, right?  Those things create a kind of echo.

(Dawai responds to someone wanting to speak) Go ahead, [Sangha 2], join on in there.

SANGHA 2:  I guess I was gonna ask about the distinction between the echoing out, and then the not—you know, not prolonging it, artificially. But I know the distinction… but it’s essentially just feeding the thoughts that are coming, that you know, start the, start the song all over again.

DAWAI:  Yeah exactly,   Well, I think you’re onto something there, because we tend to compound the echo, rather than ever letting it out. Well, it’s coming out, one way or the other, but for many beings it comes out only at death, or something serious happening.  

So we compound the echo… because, maybe I had a conversation with my family, it didn’t go so well, and now I’m going on, the next day:  “I have to get to work, I have to handle my business!”  You’re compounding.  You’re not saying “I need to be with this.  That hit me… pretty hard.  That hit my heart.”

SANGHA 2:  Well, even when, you know, you… For example, I remember, when I broke up with my ex-girlfriend, a few years back, I remember I was, like I came back home.  And you know, I  had been, for circumstances, I was able to just be with the emotion, for… I really… I couldn’t sleep, I couldn’t actually sleep, so I was just there with it.  And then, you know, if I was gonna talk percentages, like 80% of it just left, right?  But the moment I got back to where I was staying—I was living in Edinburgh back in this time—it just, you know, just kinda like the being with it… the way that I guess I was doing things.  I was doing things with it.  I was not only giving it time, but giving it too much energy, perhaps.  

DAWAI:  Exactly.

SANGHA 2:  And it’s difficult.

DAWAI:  You’re ringing.  (He pantomimes ringing a bell). You’re ringing the bell, like you said.

SANGHA 2:  Yeah.

DAWAI:  If we continuously ring the bell, then it’s not gonna echo out.  And that’s what we do,  essentially, to perpetuate cyclic existence.  I mean, we have narrations from childhood, about how life’s messed up.  You know, it’s like a 10-year-old or 12-year-old interpretation of life, that… we need to revisit that.  And say, “Well, what’s it look like now, through these eyes?”

And so in that way, we afford ourselves healing.  Even the most stubborn of us; awareness essentially forces the healing.  “You’re gonna heal, goddammit!”  

So, these are very tricky to pick up, everybody.  Like, reading the news could be: you, ringing a bell.  You could wake up in the morning, and go straight to the news, (Dawai rings the cymbals) 
and ring that bell.  And then two hours later, “Oh, it’s starting to echo out (Dawai rings the cymbals again) , I gotta ring it again.  There’s a war going on.  (ringing it again)
There’s suffering.”   (ringing it again)

On the three levels, on the dharmakaya level, on the level of totality, you’re never gonna leave those beings;  it’s fine.  On the surface, outer and inner levels, do what you can.  If you can’t do anything, you have to let it echo out.  You don’t purposefully keep suffering in there because you feel it’s righteous or something.  “Well, I have to be upset about this—I’ve been wronged, somebody else is getting wronged, and I have to keep this bell ringing.”   (Dawai taps on the cymbals).

(A few of the dogs start barking outside) Yeah, the coyotes are ringing, now…

Yeah, well that’s really what I wanted to go through.  I mean, we could formulate  (the dogs outside set up a howl) those kind of echoes. (Dawai speaks to a dog in the house) Dorje, Dorje, did you say “Woo woo”?  They like the woo woo.  They like the woo woo.  

I guess the main point, from straight from my heart, is that, you know, sometimes you might not know that you’re in an echo, or that something particular in your life is causing you these things.  But awareness will eventually expose how that’s holding your nervous system, your muscles, your tone of voice—everything is affected.  

You’re not a bad person for that.  It means that that can be nurtured.  That can be seen.  Okay?  

And really, you know, if you get a chance to just love another sentient being (several of the dogs come up to Dawai, offering and asking for affection), that’s like the counter-echo.  It really is.  Even little Yote, who’s so crazy.  Right, little coyote?  She’s a coyote-girl.  She’s a coyote-girl.  Oh, you guys get to see Yote this time.
  
(Dawai sees two other dogs waiting behind him) Little Bear is waiting in line.  There’s a line.  They’ve come to get the blessings from the Dog Yogi.  Blessings  come in the form of tasty treats... 

Yeah, so I think you’re really well-prepared.  Lots of you have, I mean, safely, are beginning to open your hearts, and allow your heart to be one with your life, and so that’s really important.  But we can’t blossom fully into that until we’re safe and ready.  So that’s what’s happening for a lot of us.  We’re just safely, on our own terms, blossoming into full awakening, full freedom.  But that full freedom, you know, that’s happening on your terms, right? Okay.

So as usual, this session was immensely powerful.  Today was—wow.  Lots of people here, totally amazing, I appreciate you all.  Always, always wishing you the best.

And so we’ll end here, with a moment of silence, dedicating any merit.  (Dawai pauses)  And deep bow to you, everybody.  Take care out there.  See you.

